# Architecture (Crowkis UI)

This repo is a **Next.js 15 App Router** marketing site + **operator app preview**. It is UI-only: no backend, no real API calls. Data is static or mock content in `src/lib/content/`. Follow these boundaries so marketing and app surfaces stay consistent and easy to extend.

---

## Two surfaces (do not mix)

| Surface | Routes | Shell | Purpose |
|---------|--------|-------|---------|
| **Marketing** | `/`, `/product`, `/docs`, `/security`, … | `SiteShell` | Public site, SEO, claim-safe product copy |
| **App preview** | `/app/*` (dashboard, tenants, settings, …) | `AppShell` via `src/app/app/layout.tsx` | Operator UI mock / control-plane preview |

Rules:
- **Marketing pages** wrap content in `<SiteShell>`. Do not use `AppShell` outside `/app/*`.
- **App pages** live under `src/app/app/` only. They inherit `AppShell` from the nested layout — do not re-wrap with `SiteShell`.
- **Cross-links** between surfaces are fine (`/app/dashboard` from marketing nav; “Back to marketing” from app). Keep hrefs as absolute paths (`/docs`, not relative `./docs`).
- Do not put marketing-only sections (hero, footer nav) inside app pages, or app tab chrome inside marketing pages.

---

## Directory layout

```
src/
├── app/                    # Routes (App Router)
│   ├── layout.tsx          # Root: fonts, metadata template, globals.css
│   ├── page.tsx            # Home (marketing)
│   ├── globals.css         # Global styles + utility classes (.glass, .section, …)
│   ├── sitemap.ts          # Public routes for SEO
│   ├── robots.ts
│   └── app/                # App preview segment (/app/*)
│       ├── layout.tsx      # AppShell wrapper
│       └── */page.tsx      # One page per app tab
├── components/
│   ├── site-shell.tsx      # Marketing header/footer (client)
│   ├── app-shell.tsx       # App tab nav (client)
│   ├── motion.tsx          # Shared framer-motion primitives
│   ├── marketing-sections.tsx
│   └── marketing/
│       └── content-page.tsx  # Standard marketing content layout
└── lib/
    ├── content.ts          # Shared constants (nav, demo metrics, tables)
    └── content/            # Domain content modules (typed, claim-safe)
        ├── types.ts
        ├── features.ts
        ├── security.ts
        └── …
```

When adding files:
- **New marketing route** → `src/app/<segment>/page.tsx`
- **New app tab** → `src/app/app/<segment>/page.tsx` + register in `AppShell` `tabs` array
- **Reusable UI** → `src/components/` (or `src/components/marketing/` if marketing-only)
- **Copy, mock data, typed claims** → `src/lib/content/` — not inline in page components

Use the `@/` import alias (`@/components/...`, `@/lib/content/...`). No deep relative imports like `../../../`.

---

## Server vs client components

**Default to Server Components** (no `"use client"`).

Add `"use client"` only when the component needs:
- React hooks (`useState`, `useEffect`, …)
- Browser APIs or event handlers that cannot live in a child client leaf
- `framer-motion` or `usePathname` (see existing shells and `motion.tsx`)

Patterns:
- **Pages** (`page.tsx`) should stay server components when possible. Import client shells/sections as children.
- **Split by boundary:** keep data-fetching and static markup in server parents; push interactivity into small client children.
- Do **not** mark entire pages `"use client"` just to use `Reveal` — import `Reveal` inside a server page (Next allows client children from server parents).
- Do **not** import server-only modules (future `fs`, heavy sync logic) into client components.

---

## Page patterns

### Marketing content pages

For standard eyebrow + title + intro + card grid pages, use `ContentPage`:

```tsx
import { Metadata } from "next";
import { ContentPage } from "@/components/marketing/content-page";
import { featurePillars } from "@/lib/content/features";

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: "Product",
  description: "…",
};

export default function ProductPage() {
  return (
    <ContentPage
      eyebrow="Product"
      title="…"
      intro="…"
      sections={featurePillars.map((item) => ({
        title: item.title,
        body: item.body,
        source: item.source,
      }))}
    />
  );
}
```

Use bespoke layouts only when the page needs a non-standard structure (home, docs hub). Prefer extending `marketing-sections.tsx` for reusable home blocks.

### App preview pages

- Compose with `glass`, grids, and `Reveal` — match existing dashboard/tenants pages.
- Pull demo numbers and table rows from `@/lib/content` or a dedicated `src/lib/content/<area>.ts` module.
- No fetch to external APIs until an explicit backend integration is added (then document env + error states in the PR).

### Metadata and SEO

- Export `metadata` (or `generateMetadata`) on every public marketing page.
- Root template is `%s | Crowkis` in `src/app/layout.tsx` — page titles should be short segment names (`Product`, `Security`).
- **New public marketing route:** add it to `src/app/sitemap.ts` `routes` array.
- App preview routes may be listed in sitemap (see current `/app/dashboard` entry); do not add unlisted private routes.

