## Content layer (claim-safe copy)

Marketing copy about Crowkis capabilities must stay **claim-safe** and traceable:

- Use `ClaimBlock` from `@/lib/content/types` for factual pillars (title, body, `source`, `confidence`, `tone: "claim-safe"`).
- Put product/security/benchmark claims in `src/lib/content/<topic>.ts`, not hardcoded in JSX.
- When adding a claim, include a **source** string (e.g. `crowkis/README.md`, internal doc path).
- Demo/metrics in `src/lib/content.ts` (`appMetrics`, `tenantRows`, …) are **illustrative** — label them as preview/mock in UI copy when ambiguous.

Do not invent undocumented product capabilities in UI text. If unsure, use softer language or add the claim to a content module with `confidence: "medium"`.

---

## Styling and design tokens

- **Tailwind first.** Extend tokens in `tailwind.config.ts` (`brand-neon`, `brand-violet`, `glass-*`, `ink`) — do not sprinkle one-off hex colors in components.
- **Global utilities** in `globals.css`: `.glass`, `.section`, `.responsive-title`, `.responsive-subtitle`, `.touch-target`, `.table-scroll`, `.faded-grid`. Reuse these before inventing new layout classes.
- **Dark theme only** — do not add light-mode branches unless explicitly requested.
- **Responsive:** mobile-first; use `sm:` / `md:` breakpoints consistently with existing pages. Interactive controls use `.touch-target` (min 44px).
- **Tables on small screens:** wrap in `.table-scroll` with `.table-compact` inner table.

Avoid inline `style={{}}` except for truly dynamic values. Prefer Tailwind utilities and existing tokens.

---

## Motion and animation

- Import **`Reveal`** and **`HoverCard`** from `@/components/motion.tsx` — do not duplicate framer-motion setup per file.
- Use `viewport={{ once: true }}` for scroll reveals (already default in `Reveal`).
- Keep motion subtle; respect `prefers-reduced-motion` if adding new animation-heavy components (consider a media-query guard).
- Limit `"use client"` surface area: shells and motion wrappers are the main client boundaries.

---

## Navigation and routing

- **Marketing nav links** come from `navLinks` in `@/lib/content`. Update that array when adding top-level marketing pages (and add matching footer links in `SiteShell` if the page is footer-worthy).
- **App tabs** are defined in `AppShell` `tabs`. New `/app/*` page → add a tab entry with matching `href`.
- Use **`next/link`** for internal navigation — not `<a href>` for in-app routes.
- **No route groups or parallel routes** unless a PR explicitly introduces them and updates this rule.

---

## What this repo does not do (yet)

- No API routes, Server Actions, or external data fetching — UI is static/mock.
- No auth/session — app preview is public demo chrome.
- No shared state library (Redux, Zustand) — local component state only.
- No test runner configured — manual + `typecheck` / `lint` / `build` for verification.

When introducing any of the above, add a short **Architecture** subsection to the PR (see `git-pr-etiquette.mdc`) and update this file if the pattern becomes standard.

---

## PR checklist for architecture changes

When your change touches structure, routing, shells, or content boundaries, confirm in the PR:

- [ ] File lives in the correct tree (`app/` vs `components/` vs `lib/content/`)
- [ ] Marketing vs app surface boundary respected
- [ ] New public route added to `sitemap.ts` (and `navLinks` / footer if applicable)
- [ ] New app tab registered in `AppShell`
- [ ] `"use client"` only where required
- [ ] Product claims in content modules with sources, not inline JSX
- [ ] Styling uses design tokens / global utilities
- [ ] `npm run typecheck`, `npm run lint`, and `npm run build` pass

---

## Anti-patterns (avoid)

- Giant `page.tsx` files with hundreds of lines of copy — move to `lib/content/`
- Duplicating header/footer markup instead of using `SiteShell` / `AppShell`
- New color hex values in components instead of `tailwind.config.ts`
- `"use client"` on every page “for convenience”
- Fetching Crowkis backend from marketing pages without env docs and error UI
- Mixing app dashboard widgets into marketing `SiteShell` pages
- Relative imports crossing more than one directory level when `@/` works
